name: The Venue Series - Part 1: The Naro Cinema
description:
This iconic landmark of Ghent was first established as The Colley Theater in 1936 but was later renamed to the Naro in the sixties after Robert Levine's parents, Nathan and Rose. Since it's opening, the Naro has been operating as Norfolk's only operating theatre feature mostly foreign and independent films.

 

Take a little piece of Ghent home with this Naro print art.

 

This print is part of a connect 4 print series. You may match them up with the Part 2 of the Series or even the Waterside series. Collect all 8 of the Venue Series for a tour of Norfolk's major venues.

name: The Venue Series - Part 1: The Chrysler Museum of Art
description:
The museum, originally entitled the Norfolk Museum of Arts and Sciences, was founded in 1933 in the Ghent district of Norfolk. After a massive donation from the automotive heir, Walter P. Chrysler, Jr., a new museum was born under the Chrysler name. Today, the museum holds over 30,000 objects around the world from a span of 5000 years. It also houses numerous sculptures and one of the world's greatest collections of glass art.

The Harrison Opera House, formally titled, The Edythe C. and Stanley L. Harrison Opera House, is the official home of the Virginia Opera. The Ghent venue was originally a WWII USO theater and was later renovated in 1993 to hold a seating capacity of 1,632.

name: The Venue Series - Part 1: Attucks Theatre
description:
In 1919, a group of African American entrepreneurs established the Attucks Theatre, located in Norfolk. The theatre was named after Crispus Attucks, who was the first to lose his life during the Revolutionary War. Known as the "Apollo Theatre of the South," it has hosted numerous performers and entertainers of various ethnicities. Today it is formally entitled as The Crispus Attucks Cultural Center. It is currently owned and operated by the City of Norfolk under the SevenVenues department.
